Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, Anglie, United Kingdom"},"da":{"1290–21 Apr 1560":"1290–21. april 1560","1290–1560":"1290–1560","1290–Female":"1290–Afdød","1310–Male":"1310–Afdød","1270–Male":"1270–Afdød","1270–Female":"1270–Afdød","1558":"1558","1315":"1315","1455":"1455","1310":"1310","1560":"1560","1382":"1382","21 Apr 1560":"21. april 1560","1270":"1270","1549":"1549","1290":"1290","1317":"1317","Inglaterra":"England","Bradfield, Yorkshire, England":"Bradfield, Jórvík, England","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1290–21 Apr 1560":"1290–21 april 1560","1290–1560":"1290–1560","1290–Female":"1290–Overleden","1310–Male":"1310–Overleden","1270–Male":"1270–Overleden","1270–Female":"1270–Overleden","1558":"1558","1315":"1315","1455":"1455","1310":"1310","1560":"1560","1382":"1382","21 Apr 1560":"21 april 1560","1270":"1270","1549":"1549","1290":"1290","1317":"1317","Inglaterra":"England","Bradfield, Yorkshire, England":"Bradfield, Yorkshire, England","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1290–21 Apr 1560":"1290–21 April 1560","1290–1560":"1290–1560","1290–Female":"1290–Deceased","1310–Male":"1310–Deceased","1270–Male":"1270–Deceased","1270–Female":"1270–Deceased","1558":"1558","1315":"1315","1455":"1455","1310":"1310","1560":"1560","1382":"1382","21 Apr 1560":"21 April 1560","1270":"1270","1549":"1549","1290":"1290","1317":"1317","Inglaterra":"England","Bradfield, Yorkshire, England":"Bradfield, Yorkshire, England","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Whitton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from Whitton in Morebattle (Roxburghshire). The placename is from Old English <i>hwīt</i> ‘white’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farm, village’, as with many of the places in 2 below.","English: habitational name from any of the places called Whitton (Durham, Lincolnshire, Middlesex, Northumberland, Shropshire, Suffolk) or Witton (Cheshire, Durham, Lancashire, Herefordshire, Norfolk, Northumberland, Warwickshire, Worcestershire, North Yorkshire); or possibly from Wyton (Huntingdonshire, East Yorkshire); or possibly from Weeton, Market Weighton, or Little Weighton (East Yorkshire). The placenames do not all share the same etymology but most of their post-medieval spellings are interchangeable. Most of the placenames derive from the Old English personal name <i>Hwīta</i> or Old English <i>hwīt</i> ‘white’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’, though some, for example Witton in Warwickshire, derive from Old English <i>wīc</i> ‘dwelling, specialized farmstead’ + <i>tūn</i>, and some others, for example Witton in Norfolk, derive from Old English <i>widu</i> ‘wood’ + <i>tūn</i>. Whitton in Lincolnshire derives from the Old English personal name <i>Hwīta</i> (genitive <i>Hwītan</i>) or Old English <i>hwīt</i> (dative <i>hwītan</i>) + <i>ēg</i> ‘island’. Witton in Lancashire derives from the Old English personal <i>Witta</i> + Old English <i>tūn</i>.","English: in Devon, this surname is a variant of   Whiddon  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Whitten","meanings":["English: variant of   Whitton   or   Whiting  ."]},{"name":"Whetten","meanings":["English, Scottish, or northern Irish: variant of   Whitton  ."]},{"name":"Whiddon","meanings":["English (Devon): habitational name from any of numerous minor places in Devon named Whiddon. Some are named with Old English <i>hwīt</i> ‘white’ + <i>dūn</i> ‘hill’ or <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’; others with Old English <i>hwǣte</i> ‘wheat’ + <i>dūn</i> or <i>denu</i> ‘valley’."]},{"name":"Whiton","meanings":["English (Essex): variant of   Whitton  . This surname is now rare in Britain.","History: James Whiton of Hingham, Norfolk, England, came to Plymouth, MA, in 1635."]}]},{"name":"Johannes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":0,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":25,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705195,"age":92,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705197,"age":165,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705201,"age":259,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705202,"age":268,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a con